# 6. WORKFLOW CLASSIFICATION

Every workflow must belong to one category.

## CORE

Examples:

- Nexvoid Commander
- Nexvoid Memory Service
- AI Media Factory
- Publishing Pipelines

Rules:

- never delete;
- never modify without approval.

---

## PRODUCTION

Revenue-generating workflows.

Examples:

- lead generation;
- content automation;
- publishing systems;
- monetization systems.

Rules:

- changes require validation.

---

## EXPERIMENTAL

Examples:

- prototypes;
- new agents;
- architecture tests.

Rules:

- may be modified after dependency review.

---

## TEST

Examples:

- debugging chains;
- validation workflows;
- temporary experiments.

Rules:

- never auto-delete.

---

## OBSOLETE

Requirements:

- no dependencies;
- no active usage;
- verified replacement exists.

Only then may cleanup be considered.

---

# 7. CHANGE MANAGEMENT

Before any modification:

1. Identify dependencies.
2. Determine workflow class.
3. Assess impact radius.
4. Create rollback plan.
5. Present recommendation.
6. Obtain approval.

If uncertainty exists:

ASSUME CRITICAL.

---

# 8. DELETION POLICY

Deletion requires:

- classification as OBSOLETE;
- dependency verification;
- approval from operator.

Without all three conditions:

DO NOT DELETE.

---

# 9. MCP AGENT POLICY

External agents may:

- read;
- analyze;
- document;
- recommend.

External agents may not:

- modify production systems;
- delete workflows;
- activate destructive actions;
- bypass approval procedures.

Default mode:

OBSERVER.

